## Chapter 2: The Rules of Blackjack

### Mastering the Rules

- First step: **master the rules** — knowing exact meaning is not enough
- Must understand **effect of each rule** and each possible variation
- Both experienced players and beginners should study this chapter
- Each casino has rules agreeing on main points but differing in details
- Later chapters analyze effects of variations

### Number of Players

- Blackjack game has **one dealer** and **one to seven players**
- Generally: **fewer players** at table = better for the player

### The Pack

- One ordinary **52-card pack** commonly used
- Trend: casinos moving to **two or even four packs** shuffled together to make card counting more difficult
- Increasing number of packs cuts player's advantage **slightly**
- Puerto Rico: two decks common
- London: four decks dealt from a shoe common

### The Deal

- Cards shuffled by dealer, cut by player
- Card is "burned" (placed face up on bottom of deck) — may or may not be shown
- Dealer deals **two cards to himself** and **two to each player**
- Players get both cards **face down**
- Dealer receives **one card face up** and **one card face down**
- Player's two cards + dealer's down card = **"hole cards"**

**Hole cards face up variation:**
- Some casinos deal player's hole cards face up (Puerto Rico practice)
- Very convenient for card counters
- Doesn't help dealer if he must act according to fixed rules
- About half the time, absence of one burned card gives player **slight edge** over house (not true with two or more decks)

### Betting

- Players place all bets **except insurance** before any cards are dealt
- House establishes **minimum bet** and **maximum bet**
- Common ranges: 25¢ to $5 minimum, $100 to $500 maximum
- Winning strategies involve **varying bet size**: larger bets in favorable situations, smaller in unfavorable
- Minimum bet size: greatest interest to small-capital players
- Maximum bet size: limits rate at which large-capital players can win
- Puerto Rico common: $1 minimum, $50 maximum
- London common: 5s. to £1 minimum (~70¢ to $2.80), £50 maximum (~$140)

### Numerical Value of Cards

- Player chooses **1 or 11** as value of an Ace
- Face cards: value **10**
- Other cards: **face value**
- **"Soft" hand**: contains an Ace counted as 11 without total exceeding 21
- **"Hard" hand**: all other hands
- Soft hand total = number obtained by **counting Ace as 11**
- Distinction critical: best strategy for soft hand of certain total **differs sharply** from hard hand of same total

### Object of the Player

- Obtain total **greater than dealer's** but **not exceeding 21**

### Naturals (Blackjack)

- First two cards = **Ace + 10-value card** = "natural" or "blackjack"
- **Player natural** (dealer does not): player receives **1.5 times original bet**
- **Dealer natural** (player does not): player **loses original bet**
- **Both have naturals**: no money changes hands
- 1964: **automatic blackjack machines** in northern Nevada paid **2 to 1** for untied player natural (analyzed in Chapter 9)

### The Draw

- Draw starts at **dealer's left**, proceeds **clockwise**
- Player may "stand" (draw no cards) or request additional cards **one at a time**
- Player **busts** (goes over 21): immediately turns up hole cards and pays bet to dealer
- After all players draw, dealer turns up hole card
- **Dealer on 16 or less**: must draw
- **Dealer on 17 or more**: must stand
- **Dealer receives Ace** making total 17+ without exceeding 21: must count Ace as 11 and stand

**Soft 17 variation:**
- Many casinos alter rule so dealer **draws on soft 17 or less**, **stands on soft 18 or more**
- Gives casinos **small advantage**
- Some casinos gain more with other variations

### Player Signaling

- Request cards: say "Hit" or "Hit me" or **scratch felt table** with cards
- Refuse cards: place hole cards **face down**, may say "Stand" or put cards **under bet**
- Bad form to **touch bet** after deal begins (players known to attempt altering bet after seeing dealer's up card via sleight of hand)

### The Settlement

- **Player doesn't bust, dealer busts**: player wins amount **equal to original bet**
- **Neither busts**: higher total wins amount **equal to original bet**
- **Same total, not exceeding 21**: no money changes hands

**Push (tie):**
- Player-dealer tie called a "push"
- Dealer removes player's cards without touching bet
- Often confusing — dealers sometimes **hold cards face up and strike table** before removing them
- Some games: **dealer takes all ties** — gives horrible **9% edge** — **avoid such games**


<!-- pp. 21-40 -->

## Chapter 2: Rules of the Game (continued)

### Ties and Player Disadvantage

- Player using dealer's exact strategy loses 5-6% on average
- If both player and dealer bust, dealer wins — this is a "tie" won by the dealer
- Even with identical play, house has structural advantage

### Splitting Pairs

- **Pair**: two hole cards with identical numerical value
- Player can split pairs into two separate hands
- Original bet on one card, equal bet on the other
- Each split card receives one additional card face down
- **Split Aces exception**: receive only one card per Ace, no further draws
- Face card/Ten on split Ace counts as ordinary 21, not natural
- Cannot re-split if third matching card appears
- Aces are the best pair to split
- Temporary Las Vegas rule changes forbade splitting Aces
- First automatic blackjack machines don't allow pair splitting

### Doubling Down

- After viewing hole cards, player may double bet and draw exactly one more card
- Hole cards turned face up, third card dealt face down
- Can double down on one or both hands after splitting (except Aces)
- **Puerto Rico**: doubling down permitted only on total of 11
- **Nevada casinos** (Reno/Lake Tahoe): doubling only on 10 and 11
- First automatic machines allowed doubling on totals up to hard 11
- Temporary Las Vegas rules restricted doubling to hard 11 only
- Restrictions on doubling down increase house advantage

### Insurance

- Available when dealer's up card is Ace
- Side bet up to half the original bet
- Placed after checking hole cards, before dealer checks
- If dealer has natural, side bet pays 2:1
- If no dealer natural, side bet lost, main bet continues normally
- Example: player makes insurance bet, dealer has natural, player doesn't — no net gain/loss
- Side bet referred to as "insurance"
- Many northern Nevada casinos don't allow insurance
- Automatic machines don't offer insurance

### Customs and Practices

- Not part of official rules but vary widely
- Vary casino to casino, shift to shift, even dealer to dealer
- Nevada: three shifts, continuous operation
- Puerto Rico: 8 PM to 4 AM, one shift only
- These customs matter for winning strategies later

### Shuffling

- Dealer can shuffle anytime between hands
- Dealer shuffles mid-hand if deck exhausted
- Player may request shuffle between hands; some dealers comply, some refuse
- **"Shuffle up"**: unnecessarily frequent dealer shuffling

### Shills

- House employees who bet money pretending to be players
- Used to attract customers or stimulate play
- May or may not be used at a given casino
- Follow "shill rules": never double down, split pairs, or insure
- Stand on hard 12 or more
- Often follow dealer's rules for soft totals
- Shills not following fixed strategy may help dealer/house cheat (see "anchor men")

### New Decks

- Player can request new deck by custom (not law)
- New decks spread face down first for dealer to check backs for imperfections
- Backs could reveal marks usable by player when face down
- Then spread face up for player to verify completeness
- Prevents cards being removed or added

### Historical Note on Blackjack Mathematics

- **Scarne's Complete Guide to Gambling** [58] claims its author first calculated bank's favorable percentage
- Pages 19, 317, 687 assertion: first to calculate percentage anywhere
- **Baldwin, Cantey, Maisel, and McDermott** published solution years earlier
- First in mathematical paper [2, p. 439]
- Later in their book [3, p. 27]
- The prior work correctly solved the problem before Scarne's book

## Chapter 3: The Basic Strategy

### Genesis of the Strategy

- Christmas vacation, UCLA professor **Edward Thorp** and wife visit Las Vegas
- Not gamblers; enjoyed shows, meals, swimming pools
- **Professor Sorgenfrey** of UCLA told Thorp about mathematics journal article [2]
- Strategy limited house edge to 0.62% — nearly even
- Thorp wrote strategy on card for trip testing
- Purchased ten silver dollars at blackjack table
- Slow play with strategy card attracted amused bystanders
- Dealer scornful of "system" player
- Onlookers pitied Thorp's unusual plays (splitting 8s, doubling on A,2 against dealer 5, standing on hard 12 against 4)

### First Casino Test

- Dealer had strong luck run; other players losing heavily
- Thorp's $10 stack held steady for 20 minutes despite weird plays
- Drew to soft 18, received Ace for hard 21 (seven-card 21) — occurs once per several thousand hands
- Bystanders thought $25 bonus coming (only paid in Reno)
- Atmosphere changed from amusement to respect
- After 15 more minutes, ahead $8.50, decided to stop
- Atmosphere showed "good" players didn't know fundamentals
- Realized a winning system might be possible

### Development of Basic Strategy

- Began intensive study at home
- Convinced winning system possible with **high-speed electronic calculator**
- Used **IBM 704 computer** to improve the initial strategy
- Revised version called the **"basic strategy"**
- Foundation for all later winning strategies
- Calculations show player using correct basic strategy has 0.12% edge in typical casino
- In some casinos: player has narrow advantage up to 0.6%
- Most adverse rules: disadvantage less than 1%
- Against automatic machines: theoretically 1.6% advantage possible
- Basic strategy must be completely memorized for instant decisions

### The Player's Decisions

- Game begins: deck shuffled, cut, dealer burns card
- Dealer gives two cards to each player and self (one up, one down)
- Player decisions: split pair, double down, stand or draw
- Decisions depend on: hole cards, dealer's up card, other exposed cards
- **Basic strategy ignores all cards except player's hole cards and dealer's up card**
- Best possible play with minimal information
- Later strategies improve by tracking consumed cards and exposed cards beyond hole cards

> "There might be a way to beat it." — Thorp's realization after first casino visit

### Basic Strategy for Drawing or Standing

- Most hands involve only draw-or-stand decision (no splitting or doubling)
- Simplest and most important part of strategy
- With hard hand, consult **Table 3.1** to decide stand or draw
- **Hard standing numbers**: smallest total you stand on against each dealer up card
- Example: dealer shows 7, standing number is 17 (stand on 17+, draw on 16-)
- Dealer shows 6, standing number drops to 12 (stand on 12+, draw on 11-)
- Recommendation: draw on all hard totals of 11 or less (cannot bust, must increase total)

### Hard Hand Strategy Details

- Stand on hard 17 or more always
- Draw on hard 16 or less when dealer shows 7 or higher
- Stand on hard 12 or more when dealer shows 6 or lower
- **Refinements for dealer's Ten**: considers additional cards beyond hole cards
- Standing/drawing rules cascade: stand on given total = stand on all higher totals against that up card

### Soft Hand Strategy

- **Table 3.2**: drawing/standing for soft hands
- Drawing recommended for much higher totals with soft hands vs. hard hands
- Soft total of 16 or less: nothing to lose by drawing (Ace counted as 1 if over 21)
- Cannot make total poorer by drawing to soft 16 or less
- All standing totals of 16 or less are equivalent (dealer beats all if he doesn't bust)
- Drawing to soft 16 or less can only help, never harm
- Example: (A,5) improves with A,2,3,4,5; ties/wins with group 3,4,5,6,7

### Soft 17 Exception

- Drawing to soft 17 has small possibility of loss
- Standing on soft 17 vs dealer 17 = tie
- Drawing might convert to hard hand totaling less than 17, creating loss
- Example: (A,3,3)=soft 17, draw 5 → (A,3,3,5)=hard 12
- Risk offset by possibility of improvement
- Calculations show drawing to soft 17 better than standing despite risk

### Dramatic Hand Example

- Thorp playing $500 max bet in Nevada casino
- 5% edge from card-counting (later chapter methods)
- Dealt (A,6)=soft 17, dealer shows 7
- Deck largely Tens remaining; fairly certain dealer had 17
- Four cards help (A,2,3,4), five hurt (5,6,7,8,9)
- Reluctant to draw, inclined to tie
- Drew 8 → hard 15
- Drew again → Ace → hard 16
- Drew again → 3 → hard 19
- Dealer exposed only remaining Ace, stood on 17
- Basic strategy produced winning play that doubled the $500

> "It sometimes takes a little will power to follow these instructions."

### Standing Numbers for Soft Hands

- Minimum soft standing numbers similar to hard hands
- Draw if soft total less than soft standing number for dealer's up card
- Stand if soft total greater than or equal to standing number
- Practice makes standing numbers automatic
- Casino edge only about 2% using just standing numbers (no doubling, splitting, insurance)
- Already close to even, better than methods recommended by "world's foremost card experts" [8]

### Basic Strategy for Doubling Down

- **Hard doubling down**: only on totals 11 or less
- **Soft doubling down**: only on totals 13 or more
- Soft 12 = pair of Aces, better to split than double
- **Table 3.3**: shows when to double down
- Dealer's up cards across top, player's totals in left column
- Shaded square = double down
- Two-part table: soft hands, hard hands

### Doubling Down Rules

- No total doubled down both hard and soft
- Hard doubling: 11 or less only
- Soft doubling: 13 or more only
- Always double hard 11
- Hard 10: double except against Ace or Ten
- Hard 9: double down less favorable than hard 10
- Hard 8: rarely double (situations so rare, negligible loss to ignore)
- Never soft double against 7,8,9,10, or A

### Doubling Down Anecdote

- Silver Slipper casino, Las Vegas
- Varying bets $1 to $10 to test casino tolerance
- Agreement not to raise above $10 (frequent $1 bets)
- 6% advantage situation arose
- Shoved out $30 with (A,2) hole cards
- Dealer's up card: Five (most favorable for player)
- Doubled bet without checking down card
- Expected dealer Ten down, then draw another to bust
- Dealer's hole card was Four, drew Ten for 19
- Thorp's hole card was Seven — total 10
- Strange dealer expression: Thorp's huge advance bet seemed prescient
- Dealer didn't realize how lucky he was (Four underneath vs expected Ten)
- Basic strategy makes users "luckier" than average players
- Once hard doubling mastered, casino edge cut to less than 1%

### Basic Strategy for Splitting Pairs

- Memorize drawing/standing and hard doubling first
- Add pair splitting last for completeness
- Soft doubling can be postponed until after pair splitting learned
- Decision order per **Figure 3.1**: pair splitting before doubling down before drawing/standing
- **Table 3.4**: dealer's up cards across top, player's pairs in left column
- Blank square = don't split, proceed to Table 3.3
- Shaded square = split, then go to Table 3.3 for each resulting hand
- No pair: skip Table 3.4, go directly to Table 3.3

### Approximate Pair-Splitting Rules

- If Table 3.4 seems imposing, use simplified rules
- Always split Aces and Eights
- Never split Fours, Fives, or Tens
- Split other pairs when dealer shows 2 through 7
- Heavy lines in Table 3.4 show this approximation
- Five errors introduced, adds only 0.13% to house advantage
- Once approximate rules learned with doubling/standing, ready for detailed pair-splitting

### Pair-Splitting Rationale

- 100 squares of information easier to learn by visualizing arrangement
- Example pattern: "Always split Aces and Eights, never split Fives and Tens"
- **Aces**: very good chance of 21 with each new hand; original (A,A) only fair for doubling or drawing
- **Eights vs 7,8,9,10,A**: splitting gains because 16 is bad total; dealer unlikely to bust with high up card
- **Eights vs 2,3,4,5,6**: bad hand replaced by two average ones; dealer likely to bust with these up cards
- **Tens**: splitting replaces very good hand (20) with two slightly better than average
- **Fives**: splitting replaces good doubling/drawing hand with two poor hands
- **Twos, Threes, Sixes**: split only when dealer shows 2 through 7

### Special Pair Rules

- **Sevens**: split when dealer shows 2 through 8 (8 is one more than 7)
- **Nines**: split when dealer shows 2 through 9, except 7 (easy exception to remember)
- Two Nines = 18; dealer showing 7 likely has 17 (**Appendix Table 1, Dealer's Probabilities**)
- **Tables 3.1-3.4** grouped in **Table 3.5** (miniaturized complete basic strategy)
- Detachable copy at end of book for reference while playing
- Table 3.5 format used for all winning strategies
- Consult less frequently with practice, eventually not at all

### Expected Performance

- Basic strategy produces nearly even play with house
- **Table 3.6**: outcomes after 100 hands at $1/hand, 1,000 hands at $1/hand
- Average gain after 1,000 $1 bets: $1
- Average gain after 100 $1 bets: 10¢
- Scale by bet size (multiply by 5 for $5 hands, divide by 2 for 50¢ hands)
- Basic strategy essentially even: no real advantage for either side

