## Addendum: Blackjack in England

### Overview of English Blackjack

- Winning systems appear to apply with full power to English blackjack
- Methods that succeeded in **Las Vegas and Puerto Rico** should work equally well in England
- Three big London gambling clubs analyzed (rules sent by English reader)
- Four decks dealt from shoe in each case (disadvantageous to player)

### Casino 1 (Most Favorable)

**Rules:**
- No card burned
- Min bet £1, max £50
- All cards dealt face up except one dealer card (considerable card counting aid)
- Player who splits pair and receives third card of same value permitted to split again (increases advantage)
- Insurance bet up to **whole amount** of original bet (not just half) — very favorable when insurance is advantageous

**Customs:**
- Dealer always deals down to and including last card
- End play can be used to tremendous advantage
- No casino can long continue head-on against expert with this rule

**Conclusions:**
- Basic-strategy player has **0.27% disadvantage**
- Average/better system player will win at more than typical rate (with end play advantage)

### Casino 2

**Rules:**
- Min 5s, max £50
- Resplitting pairs allowed
- Player who splits pair cannot double down on new hands (decreases advantage)
- Doubling down only on hard 9, 10, 11 and soft 19, 20, 21 (decreases advantage)
- Player who doubles on 9 and gets 2 may draw another card (increases advantage; refinement can be ignored)

**Customs:**
- Same as Casino 1

**Conclusions:**
- Basic-strategy player: **~0.60% disadvantage**
- System player will win at about typical rate (with end play)

### Casino 3 (Least Favorable)

**Rules:**
- Min 10s, max £50
- All cards dealt face up
- Dealer doesn't get second card until players finish (somewhat unfavorable — players lose increased stakes on dealer natural)
- Conservative approach recommended when dealer shows Ace/Ten
- Dealer with soft 17 may draw or not as he likes after seeing players' cards (quite unfavorable — dealer gains decision advantage; precise gain unknown)
- Player who splits Aces and gets third Ace may split again (max 2 splits) but not further (favorable)
- Split 10-value cards: Ace drawn to one hand counts as natural; 10-value to split Ace counts merely as 21 (variation favorable)
- Doubling down restrictions same as Casino 2
- Insurance up to whole amount (same as Casino 1)

**Customs:**
- Dealer shuffles ~20 cards before end of shoe (not serious)
- Once allowed doubling with above totals on any number of cards
- Player with hard 10/11 or soft 20/21 after doubling could redouble and receive fourth card
- Dealer dealt down to last card

**Conclusions:**
- Basic-strategy player: **~0.61% or more disadvantage**
- System player will win, but at perhaps half or less of typical rate

### Analysis Tool

> "In this way readers may analyze any casino with the aid of Table 9.2."

- Table 9.2 enables analysis of any casino's rule variations
- Computations may differ slightly from book's main tables due to refinements introduced

## Appendix: Basic Probabilities for Complete Deck

### Purpose and Scope

- Appendix for mathematically inclined readers
- Computer results for one complete deck
- Similar full datasets exist for all decks in Table 4.1
- Extreme data length (enough to fill several books) → only extract presented
- Tables usually to three decimal places (sufficient for application)
- All figures assumed to have decimal point on left (e.g., -039 = -0.039)
- Computed assuming one complete deck + Chapter 3 rules including dealer soft 17 stand

### Limitations and Applications

- Figures vary considerably if conditions altered (multi-deck, different rules)
- Deductions precisely applicable only to described situation
- Provides rough insight for multi-deck/different rules situations

### Strategy Error Analysis

- Running count errors only matter when decisions very close
- Erroneous strategy creates very small errors in close cases
- Low frequency of close decisions → minimal effect on player advantage
- Close decisions depend on specific cards drawn
- Example: hard 16 vs. dealer Ten — holding (10,4,2) = stand; holding (4,4,4,4) = player **disadvantage** of precisely 6.382% in drawing (per **Julian Braun**)
- Average player advantage drawing to 2-card hard 16 vs. Ten: 2.9% (3.2% if (8,8) split)

### Running Count vs. Detailed Strategy

- Could calculate advantage/disadvantage for each card combination making hard 16
- Consulting detailed list would be impractical (hundreds of entries, memorization impossible)
- Net gain quite small
- Running count with Tens strategy **does account for cards player draws**
- Not as precise as detailed strategy but gains much—even most—of the difference

### Table 1: Dealer's Probabilities

- Probability dealer achieves specified total for each up card value
- Rows don't add to 1.0 due to rounding/approximation (defect <10⁻⁴, negligible)
- Column totals show slight discrepancies (original had 5 figures, rounded after summing)
- Valid only assuming dealer plays all hands to conclusion even if opponents bust

> "From this point on, all tables are computed on the assumption that the dealer does not have a natural."

### Table 2a: Player's Gain Drawing vs. Standing (Hard Totals)

- Shows player gain/loss for drawing vs. standing with hard totals
- Example: hard 12 vs. dealer 2 → gain 0.038 (3.8% better to draw)
- Positive entry = draw; negative entry = stand
- Inspection yields hard standing numbers

### Table 2b: Player's Gain Drawing vs. Standing (Soft Totals)

- Same structure as 2a but for soft totals
- Yields soft standing numbers

### Close Decisions

**Two extremely close decisions** (one each in 2a and 2b):

1. **Table 2a:** Standing vs. drawing on 2-card hard 16 vs. Ten
   - Average loss: ~2.9%
   - With (10,6): loss 3.8%
   - With (9,7): loss 0.8%
   - With (8,8): loss 0.9%
   - Probability-weighted average: 2.9%
   - If (8,8) split excluded: 3.2%

2. **Table 2b:** Drawing vs. standing on soft 18 vs. Ace
   - Loses ~0.1% in such situations
   - Players attempted to solve via dealing hundreds/thousands of hands
   - Were sharply divided on these two close decisions

### Table 3: Player's Advantage Standing on Various Totals

- Computed directly from Table 1
- Example: player holds 19, dealer up card 6
  - Dealer gets poorer total (18, 17, bust): 0.1065 + 0.1670 + 0.4208 = 0.6943
  - Dealer gets better total (20, 21): 0.1007 + 0.0979 = 0.1986
  - Difference: 0.6943 - 0.1986 = 0.4957
  - Rounded to 3 figures: **0.496** (entry in Table 3)
- Player with natural always wins 1.5× original bet (150% advantage)
- No need to list natural alternative in table

### Table 4: Complete Player Strategy Analysis

- Player advantage for all possible hole card pairs vs. dealer up card
- Assumes player stands/draws using proper standing numbers (from Tables 2a, 2b)
- Shows advantage if player doubles down
- Shows advantage for numerically equal pairs if split and optimal subsequent play
- Divided into ten main sections (one per dealer up card value)

### Deriving Basic Strategy from Table 4

**For pairs:**
- Compare splitting advantage vs. doubling/standing advantage
- If splitting advantage greater → split
- Otherwise do more advantageous of doubling/standing
- Example: (4,4) vs. Ten
  - Splitting: -0.552
  - Doubling: -0.739
  - Drawing/standing (hard 16, soft 19): -0.241
  - Best = -0.241 → don't double or split

**For (A,2) symmetry:**
- (A,2) same as (2,A) → only one spot filled
- Table subsections get triangular shape

### Table 4 Insights on Basic Strategy

**Pair splitting:**
- If Aces not split: hand "only fair for doubling down or drawing or standing"
- Splitting Aces gives "a good chance for a winning hand"
- Shows precise advantage for most profitable alternative

**Rough oversimplification confirmed:**
- "Splitting pair of Eights against 7 through A breaks up a bad hand and replaces it by two average hands"
- Borne out (only roughly) by table

### Computing Overall Advantage

- Table 4 used to compute player's average advantage vs. various dealer up cards
- Overall advantage then calculated
- Similar results obtained for other decks from appropriate data
- Results listed in **Tables 4.1 and 9.2**
- Evidence of how deck composition/rule variations affect player figures

